[3] Liberia resurgence of Ebola cases
Date: 9-10 Jul 2015
Sources: various [edited]


A number of reports have come out concerning the resurgence of Ebola cases in Liberia. Selected reports are grouped here.

8 Jul 2015 Liberia: No Ebola case in Bong
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507091441.html
[Bong County Health Officer, Dr. Sampson Arzoaquoi, says there is no confirmed Ebola case in the county. Dr. Arzoaquoi's clarification comes in the wake of huge speculations in Bong that there were 2 confirmed cases at the Bong Mines Hospital in Fuamah District and Phebe Hospital in Suakoko, respectively. He said suspected Ebola cases had undergone thorough tests and proven negative ... - more]

8 Jul 2015 Liberia: Ebola cases evade detection due to ongoing lack of trust in communities
http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=51365#.VZ6TOfntmko
[In Liberia, adolescent girls trained by UNICEF and partners are part of Adolescents Leading the Intensive Fight against Ebola, or A-LIFE.

The origin of the new cluster of Ebola cases is "not yet well understood," the United Nations World Health Organization (WHO) said today [8 Jul 2015] about the outbreak in West Africa, where a residual lack of trust in the response means that some cases still evade detection for too long, increasing the risk of further transmission.]

9 Jul 2015 Liberia: New Ebola infections bring number of confirmed cases to 5
http://www.voanews.com/content/new-ebola-infections-brings-number-of-liberia-cases-to-5/2855264.html
[John Sumo, the health promotion director at Liberia's Ministry of Health, said the 2 newest cases are under investigation, and the source of the new patients' infection is unknown]

9 Jul 2015 Liberia confirms 2 new Ebola cases, 120 quarantined
http://www.necn.com/news/national-international/Liberia-Confirms-2-New-Ebola-Cases-313039191.html
[According to Dr. Francis Kateh, all 4 confirmed [living] patients are at a treatment center near Monrovia, and 14 who are considered active "high risk" contacts are being monitored.

N.B. There has been one death in addition to these 4 cases, making a total of 5 confirmed cases. -Mod.LK]

10 Jul 2015 Liberia: New jump in Ebola virus cases -- 7 in treatment units
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507101609.html?viewall=1
[According to the Deputy Incident Team Manager: There are 7 persons in the ETU. Three of the 7 are suspected cases. Three have undergone initial testing (tested negative) and are awaiting the 2nd test. Dr. Kateh, when speaking at a Ministry of Information News Conference in Monrovia, said:
120 people are under what they call "precautionary observation (voluntary).
11 of the 120 are high-risk contacts.
42 of the 120 not the highest, but high risk.
13 of the 120 are medium-risk.
49 of the 120 are low-risk.]

9 Jul 2015 Surge of Ebola in Liberia may be linked to a survivor
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/10/world/africa/surge-of-ebola-in-liberia-is-tracked-to-a-survivor.html?_r=0
[Liberia's last confirmed case, in March 2015, was also suspected to be linked to sexual transmission, because the virus isolated from that patient who died closely matched that detected in the semen of her boyfriend, who had recovered from Ebola months before she fell ill. The genome of [that] virus was different from the newly sequenced case and not thought to be connected to it.

Instead, the sequence in the new case most closely matches viruses found circulating in Liberia last July and August [2014], said Michael R. Wiley, a research scientist with the Geneva Foundation and a contractor with the United States Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases, who flew to Liberia last weekend to help sequence the virus at the Liberia Institute for Biomedical Research.

Scientists had previously shown that the Ebola virus can sometimes persist for months in certain areas of the body that are relatively protected from the immune system, including the testes, the placenta, and the inner portion of the eye. Studies of survivors in Liberia and Sierra Leone are working to determine how often this occurs. Experts recommend that survivors practice protected sex until more is known.

Liberian officials and international experts are still exploring other possibilities that could explain the new findings, including that the virus existed in an unknown reservoir before infecting at least 5 villagers. Experts believe it is unlikely that the virus has been spreading silently in recent months, given the strength of Liberia's surveillance system, including frequent testing of bodies and sick people.

Given that the virus degrades quickly, within hours to days, in the tropical heat, Dr. [Stuart] Nichol [of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention] said it was implausible that Ebola had been lying dormant in the environment [on surfaces or fomites -- Mod.JW]. He said the close similarity with other viruses found in people in Liberia last year [2014] argues against the virus having been reintroduced from wildlife. Dr. Nichol said that an initial suspicion among villagers that the illnesses might be connected to a dog "we think is a red herring."
[The dog tested negative, but since it had been buried for an unstated length of time, any virus might have been degraded. - Mod.JW]

The developments showed the power and potential of real-time genetic sequencing done in recent weeks by virologists in West Africa, said Fatorma K. Bolay, director of the Liberia Institute for Biomedical Research. The technique is also being used in Sierra Leone and Guinea, with 27 new cases last week.

In one recent example, scientists used sequencing to connect Ebola cases in 2 areas of Guinea with cases in the capital, which guided epidemiologists and anthropologists. "It helped to go back and untangle exactly how it got from one place to another," said Dr. Bruce Aylward, who leads the Ebola response for the World Health Organization. Dr. Aylward said that while secret burials and hidden illnesses were still complicating the response in Guinea and Sierra Leone, responders had been increasingly able to link new illnesses with exposure to known cases and decrease the number of chains of transmission. [Byline: Sheri Fink]

10 Jul 2015 Liberia: Tests show Ebola probably remained latent
http://www.financialexpress.com/article/lifestyle/health/tests-show-ebola-probably-remained-latent-in-liberia/98847/
[On Fri 10 Jul 2015, according to health officials, preliminary findings on analysis of the genetic sequence of the virus showed it was reactivated either possibly by sexual contact, or the virus remained undetected for weeks before surfacing again. In addition, it was also found that the virus is closely related to one that was circulating in Liberia in that particular area, and that the virus remained latent in Liberia after the country was declared Ebola-free.]
[Meaning latent in a live person or wild animal. - Mod.JW]

