[4] Suspected, vaccine, funding, research

10 Jul 2015 Australia: Child cleared of Ebola in Melbourne
http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2015/07/10/child-cleared-ebola-melbourne
[Testing has shown the child to be Ebola negative. The cause of the child's illness is unknown. The child is in isolation at the Royal Children's Hospital.]

10 Jul 2015 Nigeria: No plan to ban flights from Liberia over Ebola -- NCAA
http://dailyindependentnig.com/2015/07/no-plan-ban-liberia-flights-ebola-ncaa/

9 Jul 2015: Sierra Leone extends Ebola curfews indefinitely
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2015-07-sierra-leone-ebola-curfews-indefinitely.html

10 Jul 2015: Tanzania: nurse in self-quarantine after serving in Liberia
http://www.punchng.com/news/ebola-tanzanian-nurse-in-self-quarantine-after-serving-in-liberia/
[The nurse ("LI") is staying in a hotel for 21 days. According to LI: "One person can infect 6 others. I might be putting my family and the entire nation at risk if I ignore this precaution."]
[But what about hotel personnel? - Mod.JW]

10 Jul 2015: UK: The UK will stay the course in Sierra Leone until Ebola is defeated
https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-uk-will-stay-the-course-in-sierra-leone-until-ebola-is-defeated

9 Jul 2015 USA: The road to zero: CDC's [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention] response to the West African Ebola epidemic, 2014-2015
http://www.cdc.gov/about/ebola/index.html

Non-governmental organizations
--------------------------
8 Jul 2015 World Bank: Loss of health staff could increase maternal mortality in Ebola-hit countries
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507090451.html?viewall=1
[According to the World Bank, more than 4000 women could die from pregnancy and delivery complications in Ebola-hit countries due to the loss of doctors, nurses and midwives to the Ebola epidemic. The Ebola-related deaths of health workers could increase maternal mortality in Guinea by 38 percent, 74 percent in Sierra Leone, and more than 100 percent in Liberia.]

Funding
------
10 Jul 2015 European Union: EU pledges EUR 450 million [USD 500 million] for Ebola recovery in West Africa
http://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2015/07/10/eu-pledges-450million-euros-for-ebola-recovery-in-west-africa
[Funding is allocated as follows:
Sierra Leone: EUR 171 million / USD 190.4 million
Liberia: EUR 121 million / USD 13.5 million
Guinea: EUR 149 million / USD 166 million
"All countries affected by Ebola:" EUR 8 million / USD 8.9 million

10 Jul 2015: South Korea to offer USD 5 million in new Ebola aid
http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v8/wn/newsworld.php?id=1151797

10 Jul 2015: UN and regional leaders say USD 7 billion needed to put Ebola-affected West Africa on path to recovery
http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=51379#.VaAXULXLLnk
[Liberian President Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, speaking on behalf of Guinea, Sierra Leone, and her own country (those hardest hit by the 2014 Ebola virus outbreak) said that the funding gap for the 3 countries' national recovery plans, including the regional Mano River Union plan, is estimated to be USD 7.2 billion, which includes USD 4 billion for the region as a whole.]

11 Jul 2015 Japan: pledges additional USD 12 million for fight against Ebola
http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/07/11/national/science-health/japan-pledges-additional-12-million-for-fight-against-ebola/
[Japan on Fri [10 Jul 2015] pledged USD 11.95 million in additional assistance to West African countries fighting Ebola. Of the total, USD 10.4 million is intended for food aid, and USD 1.55 million is for technical assistance.]

11 Jul 2015 Ebola: Liberia, others to get USD 5 billion assistance from international community
http://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2015/07/11/ebola-liberia-others-to-get-5bn-assistance-from-international-community
[The international community has pledged more than USD 5 billion to support Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone in their efforts to recover from the devastating effects of Ebola. Helen Clark, United Nations Development Programme Administrator, announced this on Friday night [5 Jul 2015] in New York.

Research, vaccines
-------------
8 Jul 2015: David K Evans, Markus Goldstein, Anna Popova. Health-care worker mortality and the legacy of the Ebola epidemic. The Lancet Global Health. July 2015.
http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S2214-109X(15)00065-0
[Ebola deaths have been disproportionately concentrated among health personnel. This correspondence presents a model of how the loss of healthcare workers -- defined here as doctors, nurses, and midwives -- to Ebola might affect maternal, infant and under-5 mortality in Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone, with the aim of characterising the order of magnitude of likely effects, not providing specific predictions.]
[The predicted maternal mortality ratio is particularly striking. - Mod.LK]

9 Jul 2015: Comment: Building back better: priorities for Ebola-affected countries. The Lancet Global Health. http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S2214-109X(15)00032-7
[Summary: In April 2015, the World Bank announced USD 650 million to help Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone recover from the Ebola epidemic, including building their health systems.(1) Although there is consensus on the need for more resilient systems with greater surveillance capabilities(2), there is less clarity on how countries should pragmatically go about this undertaking. In view of the currently severe gaps in health systems whereby almost everything is needed, countries will have to set priorities for initiating this process.

(1). World Bank Group. Ebola: World Bank Group provides new financing to help Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone recover from Ebola emergency. World Bank, Washington, DC, USA; 17 Apr 2015 http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2015/04/17/ebola-world-bank-group-provides-new-financing-to-help-guinea-liberia-sierra-leone-recover-from-ebola-emergency. (accessed 1 May 2015).
(2) Kieny, MP and Dovlo, D. Beyond Ebola: a new agenda for resilient health systems. Lancet. 2015; 385: 91-92.]

9 Jul 2015 WHO statement to update on Ebola vaccine trial in Guinea
http://www.who.int/medicines/ebola-treatment/ebola-vax-guineetrials_updt/en/
[Recently, the World Health Organization (WHO) has received several inquiries on the status of the Ebola vaccine trial in Guinea. An international board of experts known as the Data Safety Monitoring Board met on 3 Jul 2015 to consider preliminary results for the vaccine efficacy trial. They concluded that the trial must continue so that more conclusive evidence can be gathered on the vaccine. The data are being submitted for peer review, an important validation step in scientific process, and will be published in a scientific journal shortly.

The vaccine clinical trial evaluates the efficacy, effectiveness and safety of a single dose of the vaccine called VSV-ZEBOV for preventing Ebola virus disease. ... The ring vaccination trial began in affected communities in Guinea on 23 Mar 2015. Since then, more than 3300 close contacts of 87 patients, including family members, neighbors, and co-workers, have volunteered to participate. ... - more]

10 Jul 2015: Ebola research efforts shift to improving survivors' health
http://www.baltimoresun.com/health/maryland-health/bs-hs-ebola-survivors-20150710-story.html
[A research partnership between USA and Liberian health officials has launched a study to learn more about the long-term health consequences of Ebola, including the risks of passing the virus to close contacts and sexual partners, and the development of long-term immunity to the virus. [Researchers at the Johns Hopkins Wilmer Eye Institute] are to lead efforts to explore the virus's effects on eye health. ...

The National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases and the Liberian Ministry of Health launched a study of the survivors last month [June 2015]. They planned to enroll about 7500 people, 1500 Ebola survivors of all ages and 6000 of their close contacts. Researchers plan to check in with the participants every 6 months for up to 5 years to closely monitor Ebola antibodies, whether the survivors can transmit the virus, and if so, whether those contacts get sick with Ebola.

Eye health
-----------
Dr. Christopher Brady and Dr. Allen Eghrari, assistant professors of ophthalmology at the Wilmer institute, are helping to lead a segment devoted to eye health. The study will include comprehensive exams to learn more about how and why the virus affects vision.

"We don't even know what the problem is," Brady said. "The major issue is to sort out exactly what are the various effects of Ebola on the eye." Theories of the effects, according to the World Health Organization, include damage to the cornea or to ocular nerves. "There's a significant need to characterize what parts of the eye [are affected] and what is the range of complications that can occur," Eghrari said. The study is based in Liberia, and the researchers hope it will also address overall eye care there. The effort will require training Liberian health care workers on how to conduct eye exams, and also making ophthalmology equipment more widely available.

"It's a valuable opportunity for us to work together with Liberian eye care providers to not only study what is needed but to build capacity in Liberia as well," Eghrari said. "The eye needs are significant, both from the immediate effects of the Ebola virus as well as other needs."

[Byline: Scott Dance]

